<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-522-668  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 522 668.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 4 1990 v24 n23 p90(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>When computerized disaster strikes. (information systemsdepartments and law suits)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kornel, Amiel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Experts warn that information systems (IS) departments may be heldresponsible when defects in a computer system cause bodily harm orproperty damage.andP;  The development and implementation of computerscan involve many individuals, and responsibility for disastertends to fall on IS because of its visibility.andP;  Systems managersare unlikely to be found personally guilty of wrongdoing, butcompanies may be faced with large judgements because plaintiffsusually press claims against parties with 'deep pockets.' More andmore professionals rely on computers for decision making, anddefects in many mission critical applications could havedisastrous consequences.andP;  Individuals and companies should avoidoverconfidence in expert systems because IS end users mustultimately take responsibility for professional actions.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Legal IssuesComputersProduct LiabilityMIS.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>